The [`time`](https://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/chrono/c/time) function can write the time to a location provided by a pointer to the function call. This pointer argument can be a null pointer, and then `time` only returns the current time.

On most systems the `time` function returns the number of seconds since an epoch, and as such is a pretty unique integer value to use for [seeding the random number generator](https://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/numeric/random/srand).

---

The single statement

    srand(time(NULL));

is equivalent to

    time_t temp_time = time(NULL);
    srand(temp_time);

Or if we want to use a non-null pointer

    time_t temp_time;
    time(&amp;temp_time);
    srand(temp_time);

